comments.body:
While this single photo doesn’t show the distinguishing characteristics clearly, Achillea borealis is the widespread, common, native Achillea species in AB.  iNat doesn’t yet accommodate the recognition of  “Achillea borealis” as a full species; “Achillea millefolium var.borealis is the (outdated)  synonym for this North American native.

Achillea millefolium (var. millefolium) is the European species, found here in gardens. It’s expected that it may have escaped here and there but that is yet to be verified.  In areas of generally-preserved habitat, Achillea borealis is the commonly-found yarrow species.

If it’s of interest, Vascular Flora of Alberta (Kershaw & Allen) is the most taxonomically up-to-date reference for this area and includes a key to the current understanding of Achillea species.
I believe this is most likely common yarrow, which is widely distributed in Alberta. Northern yarrow is less common in the Banff area.
